A degree of warmth will always live in natural hair levels 5 and below. (Warmth means the hair is still ALIVE) 
✨Unless you LIFT all the melanin out of the hair OR TONE it out. 

✨ If you TONE out the warmth, you have to tone it down. What do I mean? To achieve a cool tone, you will need to mute the warmth. Which will matte out the reflective, making the hair appear darker.
In result, the client will feel dark and ask what happened to the blonde I saw before you toned it. (And how many of you have had that conversation with a client🙋🏾‍♀️) 

PLUS: Tone is temporary, the warmth will return after a few shampoos. 

🌞 Think of it like this, the sun is bright, like gold, creating brightness and reflective light. Clouds create more chill in the air, so think of cool tones as clouds. It’s dark on a cloudy day with no sunshine. ☁️

So some will say can’t you just LIFT the hair to a PALE YELLOW to achieve a light cool tone. Yes, yes you can. If only it was this simple. As a professional hair colorist, HAIR comes before COLOR, so it’s my job to first consider the integrity of the hair BEFORE the desired hair color. 

You must consider the clients TEXTURE, DENSITY, and NATURAL HAIR COLOR LEVEL. 

If I lift out all of the melanin out to achieve the pale yellow, the hair will lose strength (keratin) and elasticity in the hair resulting in future breakage and damaged hair. ESPECIALLY for those #StyleShifters who like to do other styles besides Wash & Gos, like silk press, tape ins, braids and lace 😂 Which is my clientele excluding the lace 🫶🏾 it’s too much! #LongStoryShort 

✨✨ I say that to say, hair is not one size fits all! ✨✨

The Great Debate: Heat Damaged or Heat Trained 
ITS ALL ABOUT PERSPECTIVE! 

There are “Naturalistas” that wear their hair 98% natural and 2% pressed (straightened) …. And there are the “Naturals” that wear there hair 98% pressed and 2% natural…… and then there are those that are in between! 

✨ Heat damage is a term for those that don’t want any change to their curl elasticity. With this change to the curl pattern, the curl is damaged. Not able to spring back into formation without extra manipulation like twisting or rods. 

This damage to the curl can happen when certain texture types are pressed just once with any thermal tool. Or this can happen when hair is pressed continuously on clean or dirty hair. 
✨The issue is when the naturalista gets this silk press,  it’s the preference of both client and stylist for the hair to hold memory of the style for at least a week without reverting back before the next shampoo. BUT at times the hair holds the memory of remaining straight once shampoo, especially if you receive bleaching and silk press in the same day. Not all the time does this happen but it’s always a possibility. 

The curl may be damaged meaning the elasticity or salt bond of the hair has changed but is the hair overall actually damaged? 🤔 it’s all in perspective. Can the curl pattern regain elasticity or pattern? 

Yes, with no future straightening, natural manipulation only, and continuous trims. Depending on how often the hair was straightened, a haircut may be the only way. 

Remember it’s all in perspective because there are those that want their hair to be “Heat Trained”, don’t want a kink or curl 😂 per say, but does not want a relaxer because they want to have fun with hair color or want body & volume. They don’t want to wear their natural curl pattern because it’s not their style preference or it’s just too much work. And that’s ok! Does this mean their hair is damaged? No not necessarily, no excessive shedding or breakage and hair is still growing and thriving…. It’s all in perspective! 

The question is what do you want for YOUR HAIR? I will say the BEST OF BOTH WORLDS is a very hard thing to obtain.

Let’s continue this conversation 👇🏾

There is a lot to consider when a client is looking to change their hair color. 

1. The Color History - which in this clients case was a level 5 Demi permanent chocolate base used as a shadow/root smudge to her lived in balayage. 

2. The Process - to achieve the level of lightness for the desired copper gold hair color it would require a global bleach application for consistency of level. 

3. The Maintenance- the regrowth and transition of the pre lifted base and upkeep to maintain the vibrancy. 

4. The health of the hair - the pre lifting in cooler months Fall / Winter at the root can result in a dryer scalp and more maintenance to not cause banding or a line of demarcation. As well as weaken hair since clients wears silk press and wash&go styles. 

✨ Tip- use @redken Color Gel Oils Clear with 20 volume to gently remove a Demi permanent hair color for a lighter undertone for better reflectance of the permanent hair color. #ThankMeLater

100% Grey Coverage using @redken Color Gel Oils 

How?! 

✨ The double N (NN) gives me double of the natural pigment needed for more a matted finish. 

✨✨ The Bonus is the extra pigmented gloss to be sure the color isn’t hollow… using @redken #ShadesEQ 04NB & 06NB… with red being one of the contributing pigments in this shade.. it helps provide more depth to the hair 🤎

✨ Saturation, Saturation, Saturation… I used a total of 8oz of color for a full application… you can’t be stingy with the color.
